definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-mevalonate + CoA + 2 NAD(+) -eq- (S)-3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA + 2 H(+) + 2 NADH.

Catalysis of the addition of the second glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation -  the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Glc(1)Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.

Catalysis of the introduction of a trans double bond between C4 and C5 of the long chain base region of a sphingolipid. Sphingolipids are composed of a long chain base (LCB) amide-linked to a very long chain fatty acid.
Catalysis of the transfer of a xylosyl group to an acceptor molecule, typically another carbohydrate or a lipid.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (S)-4-amino-5-oxopentanoate -eq- 5-aminolevulinate.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with major histocompatibility complex molecules -  a set of molecules displayed on cell surfaces that are responsible for lymphocyte recognition and antigen presentation.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with major histocompatibility complex class I molecules -  a set of molecules displayed on cell surfaces that are responsible for lymphocyte recognition and antigen presentation.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with major histocompatibility complex class II molecules -  a set of molecules displayed on cell surfaces that are responsible for lymphocyte recognition and antigen presentation.
Catalysis of the activation of the small ubiquitin-related modifier URM1, through the formation of an ATP-dependent high-energy thiolester bond.
Catalysis of the activation of the small ubiquitin-related modifier Hub1, through the formation of an ATP-dependent high-energy thiolester bond.
Catalysis of the transfer of URM1 from one protein to another via the reaction X-URM1 + Y ---gt- Y-URM1 + X, where both X-URM1 and Y-URM1 are covalent linkages.
Catalysis of the transfer of ISG15 from one protein to another via the reaction X-ISG15 + Y ---gt- Y-ISG15 + X, where both X-ISG15 and Y-ISG15 are covalent linkages.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (S)-2,3-epoxysqualene -eq- lupeol. This reaction is the cyclization of (S)-2,3-epoxysqualene (2,3-oxidosqualene) to lupeol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (S)-2,3-epoxysqualene -eq- beta-amyrin. This reaction is the cyclization and rearrangement of (S)-2,3-epoxysqualene (2,3-oxidosqualene) into beta-amyrin.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with phosphate.
The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a cuticle.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with bacteriochlorophyll, a form of chlorophyll found in photosynthetic bacteria, such as the purple and green bacteria. There are several types, designated a to g. Bacteriochlorophyll a and bacteriochlorophyll b are structurally similar to the chlorophyll a and chlorophyll b found in plants.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the hypocretin receptor.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine + heparan sulfate -eq- UDP + (N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl)-heparan sulfate.

label.value: structural constituent of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle

definition.value: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle. An example of this process is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.
The orientation of free radical substrates in such a way that only a particular stereoisomer is synthesized by an enzyme. Best characterized as a function during lignan biosynthesis.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP-6-deoxy-D-mannose + NAD(P)+ -eq- GDP-4-dehydro-6-deoxy-D-mannose + NAD(P)H + H+. In the reverse reaction, a mixture of GDP-D-rhamnose and its C-4 epimer is formed.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any chemokine receptor.
Catalysis of the formation of both isopentenyl pyrophosphate and dimethylallyl pyrophosphate from (E)-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl pyrophosphate.
Discrete subnuclear bodies in the interchromatin nucleoplasmic space, often located adjacent to nuclear specks. 10-20 paraspeckles are typically found in human cell nuclei.

The outer membrane of a muscle cell, consisting of the plasma membrane, a covering basement membrane (about 100 nm thick and sometimes common to more than one fiber), and the associated loose network of collagen fibers.

A myosin complex containing a class III myosin heavy chain and associated light chains -  myosin III is monomeric myosin that serves as a link between the cytoskeleton and the signaling complex involved in phototransduction, and differs from all other myosins in having an N-terminal kinase domain.
Catalysis of the introduction of an omega-3 double bond into the fatty acid hydrocarbon chain.
Catalysis of the reaction -  sphingosine 1-phosphate + H2O -eq- sphingosine + phosphate.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a histone, any of a group of water-soluble proteins found in association with the DNA of plant and animal chromosomes. They are involved in the condensation and coiling of chromosomes during cell division and have also been implicated in nonspecific suppression of gene activity.
An intranuclear focus at which aggregated proteins have been sequestered.

label.value: extrinsic component of endoplasmic reticulum membrane

definition.value: The component of the endoplasmic reticulum membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + caffeoyl-CoA -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + feruloyl-CoA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + CoA + pimelate -eq- AMP + diphosphate + H(+) + pimelyl-CoA.

label.value: dosage compensation by hypoactivation of X chromosome

definition.value: Compensating for the two-fold variation in X - autosome chromosome ratios between sexes by an inactivation of a proportion of genes on both of the X chromosomes of the XX sex, leading to a decrease, of half, of the levels of gene expression from these chromosomes. An example of this process is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.
Catalysis of the reduction of versicolorin A to sterigmatocystin.
A tissue-specific, membrane-bounded cytoplasmic organelle within which melanin pigments are synthesized and stored. Melanosomes are synthesized in melanocyte cells.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a lipopeptide containing a nonprotein moiety consisting of three acyl groups.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a lipopeptide containing a nonprotein moiety consisting of two acyl groups.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of nonterminal peptide bonds in a polypeptide chain, occurring within a membrane.
A hexameric protein complex required for the initiation and regulation of DNA replication.

label.value: eukaryotic elongation factor-2 kinase regulator activity

definition.value: Modulates the activity of the enzyme eukaryotic elongation factor-2 kinase.

label.value: eukaryotic elongation factor-2 kinase activator activity

definition.value: Increases the activity of the enzyme eukaryotic elongation factor-2 kinase.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (S)-2,3-epoxysqualene -eq- alpha-amyrin. This reaction is a cyclization and rearrangement of (S)-2,3-epoxysqualene (2,3-oxidosqualene) into alpha-amyrin.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any hormone, naturally occurring substances secreted by specialized cells that affect the metabolism or behavior of other cells possessing functional receptors for the hormone.

A protein complex which usually consists of three components, e.g. in Xenopus, the importin alpha-subunit|CAS|Ran, and which functions to shuttle the importin alpha-subunit out of the nucleus through the nuclear pore.

A protein complex which usually consists of three components, e.g. in Xenopus, the importin alpha and beta-subunits and any protein which has a nuclear localization sequence (NLS). The complex acts to import proteins with an NLS into the nucleus through a nuclear pore.

A complex which usually consists of three components, e.g. in Xenopus and yeast, the export receptor CRM1 (also known as exportin 1), the Ran protein and any RNA with a nuclear export sequence (NES). The complex acts to export RNA molecules with a NES from the nucleus through a nuclear pore.
A spherical, membrane-bounded organelle found in some anaerobic protozoa, which participates in ATP and molecular hydrogen formation.

A complex of three proteins, which in animals is approximately 150kDa and consists of the insulin-like growth factor (IGF), the insulin-like growth factor binding protein-3 (IGFBP-3), or -5 (IGFBP-5) and an acid-labile subunit (ALS). The complex plays a role in growth and development.
